# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: holborn-viaduct-power-station
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] In an electric circuit, instantaneous power is the time rate of flow of energy past a given point of the circuit.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] In alternating current circuits, energy storage elements such as inductors and capacitors may result in periodic reversals of the direction of energy flow.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] The portion of instantaneous power that, averaged over a complete cycle of the AC waveform, results in net transfer of energy in one direction is known as instantaneous active power, and its time average is known as **active power** or **real power**.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] The portion of instantaneous power that results in no net transfer of energy but instead oscillates between the source and load in each cycle due to stored energy is known as instantaneous reactive power, and its amplitude is the absolute value of **reactive power**.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] The **instantaneous power** is given by the product: $p(t)=v(t)i(t)=2{|V|}{|I|}\cos(\omega t)\cos(\omega t-\varphi ).$ If the load is purely resistive, the two quantities reverse their polarity at the same time.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Hence, the instantaneous power is always positive, such that the direction of energy flow does not reverse and always is toward the resistor.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] In this case, only active power is transferred.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] If the load is purely *reactive*, then the voltage and current are 90 degrees out of phase.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] For two quarters of each cycle, the product of voltage and current is positive, but for the other two quarters, the product is negative, indicating that on average, exactly as much energy flows into the load as flows back out.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] There is no net energy flow over each half cycle.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] In this case, only reactive power flows: There is no net transfer of energy to the load; however, electrical power does flow along the wires and returns by flowing in reverse along the same wires.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] The current required for this reactive power flow dissipates energy in the line resistance, even if the ideal load device consumes no energy itself.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Practical loads have resistance as well as inductance, or capacitance, so both active and reactive powers will flow to normal loads.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Apparent power is the product of the RMS values of voltage and current.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Apparent power is taken into account when designing and operating power systems, because although the current associated with reactive power does no work at the load, it still must be supplied by the power source.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Conductors, transformers and generators must be sized to carry the total current, not just the current that does useful work.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Insufficient reactive power can depress voltage levels on an electrical grid and, under certain operating conditions, collapse the network (a blackout).
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Another consequence is that adding the apparent power for two loads will not accurately give the total power unless they have the same phase difference between current and voltage (the same power factor).
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Conventionally, capacitors are treated as if they generate reactive power, and inductors are treated as if they consume it.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] If a capacitor and an inductor are placed in parallel, then the currents flowing through the capacitor and the inductor tend to cancel rather than add.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] This is the fundamental mechanism for controlling the power factor in electric power transmission; capacitors (or inductors) are inserted in a circuit to partially compensate for reactive power 'consumed' ('generated') by the load.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Purely capacitive circuits supply reactive power with the current waveform leading the voltage waveform by 90 degrees, while purely inductive circuits absorb reactive power with the current waveform lagging the voltage waveform by 90 degrees.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] The result of this is that capacitive and inductive circuit elements tend to cancel each other out.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] These are all denoted in the adjacent diagram (called a power triangle).
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] In the diagram, *P* is the active power, *Q* is the reactive power (in this case positive), *S* is the complex power and the length of *S* is the apparent power.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Reactive power does not do any work, so it is represented as the **imaginary axis** of the vector diagram.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Active power does do work, so it is the real axis.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] The unit for power is the watt (symbol: W).
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Apparent power is often expressed in volt-amperes (VA) since it is the product of RMS voltage and RMS current.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] The unit for reactive power is var, which stands for volt-ampere reactive.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Since reactive power transfers no net energy to the load, it is sometimes called "wattless" power.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] It does, however, serve an important function in electrical grids and its lack has been cited as a significant factor in the Northeast blackout of 2003.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Understanding the relationship among these three quantities lies at the heart of understanding power engineering.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] The mathematical relationship among them can be represented by vectors or expressed using complex numbers, *S* = *P* + *j Q* (where *j* is the imaginary unit).
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] where V and I are the complex valued voltage and current, respectively, written in phasor form with the amplitude as RMS.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Also by convention, the complex conjugate of *I* is used, which is denoted $I^{*}$ (or ${\overline {I}}$ ), rather than *I* itself.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] This is done because otherwise using the product V I to define S would result in a quantity that depends on the reference angle chosen for V or I, but defining S as V I* results in a quantity that doesn't depend on the reference angle and allows to relate S to P and Q.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Other forms of complex power (units in volt-amps, VA) are derived from *Z*, the load impedance (units in ohms, Ω).
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] where *X* denotes reactance (units in ohms, Ω) of the load.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] These are simplified diagrammatically by the power triangle.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] The ratio of active power to apparent power in a circuit is called the power factor.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] For two systems transmitting the same amount of active power, the system with the lower power factor will have higher circulating currents due to energy that returns to the source from energy storage in the load.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] These higher currents produce higher losses and reduce overall transmission efficiency.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] A lower power factor circuit will have a higher apparent power and higher losses for the same amount of active power.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] The power factor is 1.0 when the voltage and current are in phase.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] It is zero when the current leads or lags the voltage by 90 degrees.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] When the voltage and current are 180 degrees out of phase, the power factor is negative one, and the load is feeding energy into the source (an example would be a home with solar cells on the roof that feed power into the power grid when the sun is shining).
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Power factors are usually stated as "leading" or "lagging" to show the sign of the phase angle of current with respect to voltage.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Voltage is designated as the base to which current angle is compared, meaning that current is thought of as either "leading" or "lagging" voltage.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Where the waveforms are purely sinusoidal, the power factor is the cosine of the phase angle ( $\varphi$ ) between the current and voltage sinusoidal waveforms.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Equipment data sheets and nameplates will often abbreviate power factor as " $\cos \varphi$ " for this reason.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Example: The active power is 700 W and the phase angle between voltage and current is 45.6°.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] In a direct current circuit, the power flowing to the load is proportional to the product of the current through the load and the potential drop across the load.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] The power that happens because of a capacitor or inductor is called reactive power.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] It happens because of the AC nature of elements like inductors and capacitors.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Energy flows in one direction from the source to the load.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] In AC power, the voltage and current both vary approximately sinusoidally.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] When there is inductance or capacitance in the circuit, the voltage and current waveforms do not line up perfectly.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] The power flow has two components – one component flows from source to load and can perform work at the load; the other portion, known as "reactive power", is due to the delay between voltage and current, known as phase angle, and cannot do useful work at the load.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] It can be thought of as current that is arriving at the wrong time (too late or too early).
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] To distinguish reactive power from active power, it is measured in units of "volt-amperes reactive", or var.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] These units can simplify to watts but are left as var to denote that they represent no actual work output.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Energy stored in capacitive or inductive elements of the network gives rise to reactive power flow.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Reactive power flow strongly influences the voltage levels across the network.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Voltage levels and reactive power flow must be carefully controlled to allow a power system to be operated within acceptable limits.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] A technique known as reactive compensation is used to reduce apparent power flow to a load by reducing reactive power supplied from transmission lines and providing it locally.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] For example, to compensate an inductive load, a shunt capacitor is installed close to the load itself.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] This allows all reactive power needed by the load to be supplied by the capacitor and not have to be transferred over the transmission lines.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] This practice saves energy because it reduces the amount of energy that is required to be produced by the utility to do the same amount of work.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Additionally, it allows for more efficient transmission line designs using smaller conductors or fewer bundled conductors and optimizing the design of transmission towers.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Stored energy in the magnetic or electric field of a load device, such as a motor or capacitor, causes an offset between the current and the voltage waveforms.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] A capacitor is a device that stores energy in the form of an electric field.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] As current is driven through the capacitor, charge build-up causes an opposing voltage to develop across the capacitor.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] This voltage increases until some maximum dictated by the capacitor structure.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] In an AC network, the voltage across a capacitor is constantly changing.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] The capacitor opposes this change, causing the current to lead the voltage in phase.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Capacitors are said to "source" reactive power, and thus to cause a leading power factor.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Induction machines are some of the most common types of loads in the electric power system today.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] These machines use inductors, or large coils of wire to store energy in the form of a magnetic field.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] When a voltage is initially placed across the coil, the inductor strongly resists this change in a current and magnetic field, which causes a time delay for the current to reach its maximum value.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] This causes the current to lag behind the voltage in phase.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Inductors are said to "sink" reactive power, and thus to cause a lagging power factor.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Induction generators can source or sink reactive power, and provide a measure of control to system operators over reactive power flow and thus voltage.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Because these devices have opposite effects on the phase angle between voltage and current, they can be used to "cancel out" each other's effects.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] This usually takes the form of capacitor banks being used to counteract the lagging power factor caused by induction motors.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Transmission connected generators are generally required to support reactive power flow.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] For example, on the United Kingdom transmission system, generators are required by the Grid Code Requirements to supply their rated power between the limits of 0.85 power factor lagging and 0.90 power factor leading at the designated terminals.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] The "system gain" is an important source of reactive power in the above power balance equation, which is generated by the capacitative nature of the transmission network itself.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] By making decisive switching actions in the early morning before the demand increases, the system gain can be maximized early on, helping to secure the system for the whole day.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] To balance the equation some pre-fault reactive generator use will be required.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Other sources of reactive power that will also be used include shunt capacitors, shunt reactors, static VAR compensators and voltage control circuits.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] While active power and reactive power are well defined in any system, the definition of apparent power for unbalanced polyphase systems is considered to be one of the most controversial topics in power engineering.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Originally, apparent power arose merely as a figure of merit.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Major delineations of the concept are attributed to Stanley's *Phenomena of Retardation in the Induction Coil* (1888) and Steinmetz's *Theoretical Elements of Engineering* (1915).
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] However, with the development of three-phase power distribution, it became clear that the definition of apparent power and the power factor could not be applied to unbalanced polyphase systems.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] In 1920, a "Special Joint Committee of the AIEE and the National Electric Light Association" met to resolve the issue.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] that is, the magnitude of total three-phase complex power.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] The 1920 committee found no consensus and the topic continued to dominate discussions.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] In 1932, another committee formed and once again failed to resolve the question.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] The transcripts of their discussions are the lengthiest and most controversial ever published by the AIEE.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Further resolution of this debate did not come until the late 1990s.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] $V^{+}$ denotes the positive sequence voltage phasor, and $I^{+}$ denotes the positive sequence current phasor.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] A perfect resistor stores no energy; so current and voltage are in phase.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Therefore, there is no reactive power and $P=S$ (using the passive sign convention).
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] For a perfect capacitor or inductor, there is no net power transfer; so all power is reactive.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] where *X* is the reactance of the capacitor or inductor.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] where $v(t)$ and $i(t)$ are the time-varying voltage and current waveforms.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] This definition is useful because it applies to all waveforms, whether they are sinusoidal or not.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] This is particularly useful in power electronics, where non-sinusoidal waveforms are common.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] In general, engineers are interested in the active power averaged over a period of time, whether it is a low frequency line cycle or a high frequency power converter switching period.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] This method of calculating the average power gives the active power regardless of harmonic content of the waveform.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Since an RMS value can be calculated for any waveform, apparent power can be calculated from this.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] For active power it would at first appear that it would be necessary to calculate many product terms and average all of them.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] However, looking at one of these product terms in more detail produces a very interesting result.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] However, the time average of a function of the form cos(*ωt* + *k*) is zero provided that *ω* is nonzero.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Therefore, the only product terms that have a nonzero average are those where the frequency of voltage and current match.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] In other words, it is possible to calculate active (average) power by simply treating each frequency separately and adding up the answers.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Furthermore, if voltage of the mains supply is assumed to be a single frequency (which it usually is), this shows that harmonic currents are a bad thing.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] They will increase the RMS current (since there will be non-zero terms added) and therefore apparent power, but they will have no effect on the active power transferred.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Hence, harmonic currents will reduce the power factor.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Harmonic currents can be reduced by a filter placed at the input of the device.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] Typically this will consist of either just a capacitor (relying on parasitic resistance and inductance in the supply) or a capacitor-inductor network.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ac-power] An active power factor correction circuit at the input would generally reduce the harmonic currents further and maintain the power factor closer to unity.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] "Ancillary services are all services required by the transmission or distribution system operator to enable them to maintain the integrity and stability of the transmission or distribution system as well as the power quality".
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] Ancillary services are specialty services and functions provided by actors within the electric grid that facilitate and support the continuous flow of electricity, so that the demand for electrical energy is met in real time.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] The term ancillary services is used to refer to a variety of operations beyond generation and transmission that are required to maintain grid stability and security.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] These services generally include active power control or frequency control and reactive power control or voltage control, on various timescales.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] Traditionally, ancillary services have been provided by large production units such as synchronous generators.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] With the integration of more intermittent generation and the development of smart grid technologies, the provision of ancillary services is extended to smaller distributed generation and consumption units.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] Electricity frequency is directly connected to the balance of consumption and generation of active power ( $\Delta P=P_{generation}-P_{consume}$ ) and the total rotating energy ( $W_{tot,kin}$ ) of the synchronous power system.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] Where S is the total exchange of active power for the entire grid and H is the normalized inertia constant for the system.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] A system with a small amount of total rotating kinetic energy will be more sensitive to deviations in $\Delta P$ , as the frequency's derivative will be more significantly affected.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] As the total inertia of synchronous grids decreases due to the increasing integration of renewable generation sources, the methodologies and requirements for enabling converter-based generation units to control grid frequency with greater speed and precision are becoming more important.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] Frequency control refers to the need to ensure that the grid frequency stays within a specific range of the nominal frequency.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] Mismatch between electricity generation and demand causes variations in frequency, so control services are required to bring the frequency back to its nominal value and ensure it does not vary out of range.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] where Pm is the change in power of the system.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] If we have multiple generators, each might have its own R.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] This simple equation can be rearranged to find the change in power that corresponds to a given change in frequency.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] Consumer loads expect voltage within a certain range, and the regulators require it be within a certain percent of the nominal voltage (for example, in the US it is ±5%).
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] Reactive power can be used to compensate the voltage drops, but must be provided closer to the loads than real power needs (this is because reactive power tend to travel badly through the grid).
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] Notice that voltage can be controlled also using transformer taps and voltage regulators.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] Scheduling and dispatch are necessary because in most electrical systems energy storage is nearly zero, so at any instant, the power into the system (produced by a generator) must equal the power out of the system (demand from consumers).
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] Since production must so closely match demand, careful scheduling and dispatch are necessary.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] Usually performed by the independent system operator or transmission system operator, both are services dedicated to the commitment and coordination of the generation and transmission units in order to maintain the reliability of the power grid.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] Scheduling refers to before-the-fact actions (like scheduling a generator to produce a certain amount of power the next week), while dispatch refers to the real-time control of the available resources.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] Since production and demand must match so perfectly (see Scheduling and dispatch), operating reserves help make up the difference when production is too low.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] An operating reserve is a generator that can quickly be dispatched to ensure that there is sufficient energy generation to meet load.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] Spinning reserves are generators that are already online and can rapidly increase their power output to meet fast changes in demand.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] Spinning reserves are required because demand can vary on short timescales and rapid response is needed.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] Other operating reserves are generators that can be dispatched by the operator to meet demand, but that cannot respond as quickly as spinning reserves, and grid battery storage that can respond within tens of milliseconds, generally faster than even spinning reserve.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] The grid integration of renewable generation simultaneously requires additional ancillary services and has the potential to provide ancillary services to the grid.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] The inverters that are installed with distributed generation systems and roof top solar systems have the potential to provide many of the ancillary services that are traditionally provided by spinning generators and voltage regulators.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] These services include reactive power compensation, voltage regulation, flicker control, active power filtering and harmonic cancellation.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] Wind turbines with variable-speed generators have the potential to add synthetic inertia to the grid and assist in frequency control.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] CAISO tested the 131 MW Tule wind farm's synchronverter in 2018, and found it could perform some of the grid services similar or better than traditional generators.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] Hydro-Québec began requiring synthetic inertia in 2005 as the first grid operator, demanding a temporary 6% power boost when countering frequency drop by combining the power electronics with the rotational inertia of a wind turbine rotor.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] Similar requirements came into effect in Europe in 2016.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] Plug-in electric vehicles have the potential to be utilized to provide ancillary services to the grid, specifically load regulation and spinning reserves.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] Plug-in electric vehicles can behave like distributed energy storage and have the potential to discharge power back to the grid through bidirectional flow, referred to as vehicle-to-grid (V2G).
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] Plug-in electric vehicles have the ability to supply power at a fast rate which enables them to be used like spinning reserves and provide grid stability with the increased use of intermittent generation such as wind and solar.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] According to the study cited in the reference, which compared the profitability of offering operating reserve ancillary service with the sales of V2G energy from a fleet of vehicles, providing operating reserve regulation service is more profitable than selling V2G energy alone.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/ancillary-services] However, the technologies to utilize electric vehicles to provide ancillary services are not yet widely implemented, but there is much anticipation of their potential.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] An **arc-fault circuit interrupter** (**AFCI**) or **arc-fault detection device** (**AFDD**) is a circuit breaker that breaks the circuit when it detects the electric arcs that are a signature of loose connections in home wiring.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Loose connections, which can develop over time, can sometimes become hot enough to ignite house fires.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] An AFCI selectively distinguishes between a harmless arc (incidental to normal operation of switches, plugs, and brushed motors), and a potentially dangerous arc (that can occur, for example, in a lamp cord which has a broken conductor).
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] In regions using 230 V, the combination of higher voltage and lower load currents lead to different conditions being required to initiate an arc fault that does not either burn clear or weld to a short circuit after a short time, and there are different arc characteristics once struck.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Because of this, in Western Europe (where in many countries a domestic supply may be 400V 3 phase) and the UK (where domestically a single phase 230V supply is common), adoption is slower, and their use is optional, only being mandated in specified high risk locations.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] The Australian and New Zealand regulations – Wiring Rules (AS NZS 3000:2018) do not require installation of AFDDs in Australia.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] However, in New Zealand all final sub-circuits with ratings up to 20 A will require protection by an AFDD if they supply locations with significant fire risk, locations containing irreplaceable items, certain historic buildings, and socket-outlets in school sleeping accommodation.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Most sockets in these countries are on circuits rated at 20 A or less.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] In the US, arc faults are said to be one of the leading causes for residential electrical fires.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Each year in the United States, over 40,000 fires are attributed to home electrical wiring.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] These fires result in over 350 deaths and over 1,400 injuries each year.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Conventional circuit breakers respond only to overloads and short circuits, so they do not protect against arcing conditions that produce erratic, and often reduced current.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] AFCIs are devices designed to protect against fires caused by arcing faults in the home electrical wiring.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] The AFCI circuitry continuously monitors the current and discriminates between normal and unwanted arcing conditions.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Once detected, the AFCI opens its internal contacts, thus de-energizing the circuit and reducing the potential for a fire to occur.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] The electronics inside an AFCI breaker detect electrical current alternating at characteristic frequencies, usually around 100 kHz, known to be associated with wire arcing, which are sustained for more than a few milliseconds.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] A *combination AFCI breaker* provides protection against parallel arcing (line to neutral), series arcing (a loose, broken, or otherwise high resistance segment in a single line), ground arcing (from line or neutral to ground), overload, and short circuit.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] The AFCI will open the circuit if dangerous arcing is detected.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] When installed as the first outlet on a branch circuit, AFCI receptacles provide series arc protection for the entire branch circuit.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] They also provide parallel arc protection for the branch circuit starting at the AFCI receptacle.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Unlike AFCI breakers, AFCI receptacles may be used on any wiring system regardless of the panel.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Starting with the 1999 version of the *National Electrical Code* in the United States, and the 2002 version of the *Canadian Electrical Code* in Canada, the national codes require AFCIs in all circuits that feed outlets in bedrooms of dwelling units.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] They are also required in dormitory units.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Not all U.S. jurisdictions have adopted the NEC's AFCI requirements so it is important to check local code requirements.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] The AFCI is intended to prevent fire from arcs.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] AFCI circuit breakers are designed to meet one of two standards as specified by UL 1699: "branch" type or "combination" type (note: the Canadian Electrical Code uses different terminology but similar technical requirements).
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] A branch type AFCI trips on 75 amperes of arcing current from the line wire to either the neutral or ground wire.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] A combination type adds series arcing detection to branch type performance.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Combination type AFCIs trip on 5 amperes of series arcing.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] AFCI receptacles are an alternative solution to AFCI breakers.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] These receptacles are designed to address the dangers associated with both types of potentially hazardous arcing: parallel and series.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] AFCI receptacles offer the benefit of localized *test* and *reset* with such buttons located on the face of the device.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] This can save a journey to the breaker panel but can also encourage simply resetting by a user without investigating the underlying fault, as would presumably happen if someone with access to the electrical panel was notified.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] In 2002, the NEC removed the word "receptacle", leaving "outlets", with the effect that lights and other wired-in devices such as ceiling fans within bedrooms were added to the requirement.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] The 2005 code made it clearer that all outlets must be protected despite discussion in the code-making panel about excluding bedroom smoke detectors from the requirement.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] "Outlets" as defined in the NEC includes receptacles, light fixtures and smoke alarms, among other things.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Basically, any point where AC electricity is used to power something is an outlet.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] As of January 2008, only "combination type" AFCIs meet the NEC requirement.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] The 2008 NEC requires the installation of combination-type AFCIs in all 15 and 20 ampere residential circuits with the exception of laundries, kitchens, bathrooms, garages, and unfinished basements, though many of these require GFCI protection.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] The 2014 NEC adds kitchens and laundry rooms to the list of rooms requiring AFCI circuitry, as well as any devices (such as lighting) requiring protection.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] As of January 2023, there are a total of 6 means of protection covered as part of 210.12(A).
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] A listed branch/feeder-type AFCI that is installed at the origin of the branch circuit working in combination with the listed outlet branch-circuit-type AFCI (OBC AFCI) installed at the first outlet box which must also be marked that it is the first outlet box of the branch circuit.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] This option includes a listed "Supplemental Arc Protection Circuit Breaker" which does not exist.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] There is no standard for this device and so this is not an option that can be used.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] This option does have a single manufacturer who has a solution on the market.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] (b) Maximum length for a 14 AWG conductor is 50 ft and the maximum length for a 12 AWG conductor is 70ft.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] (c) The first outlet box has to be marked as such.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] (d) The circuit breaker and the OBC AFCI must be listed to meet the requirements of a system combination-type AFCI.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Options 5 and 6 are the same options as we've seen in this section in the past but just included as positive text instead of being an exception.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] In the UK, the Wiring Regulations 18th edition (BS 7671:2018) is the first edition to make any mention of arc fault devices, and indicate they may be installed if the design has an unusually high risk of fire from arc faults.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] The annexes relating to testing indicate that when AFDDs are installed, their correct operation must be verified before completion, but the method of testing is not described.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] This is in contrast to RCDs where a number of trip times at different fault current levels must be verified.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Most power circuits in these countries fall under this clause as the common sockets are 10 A and 15 A rating.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] The Australian standards are used in Argentina, Fiji, Tonga, Solomon Islands and Papua New Guinea.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] AFCIs are designed to protect against fires caused by electrical arc faults.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] While the sensitivity of the AFCIs helps in the detection of arc faults, these breakers can also indicate false positives by identifying normal circuit behaviors as arc faults.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] For instance, lightning strikes provide voltage and current profiles that resemble arc faults, and vacuum cleaners and some laser printers trip AFCIs.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] This nuisance tripping reduces the overall effectiveness of AFCIs.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Research into advancements in this area is being pursued.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Sensitivities and mitigation have been known since 2013.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] AFCI circuit breakers include a standard inverse-time circuit breaker but provide no specific protection against "glowing" connections (also known as a high resistance connection), high line voltages, or low line voltages.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] An AFCI does not detect high line voltage caused by an open neutral in a multiwire branch circuit.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] A multiwire branch circuit uses both energized wires of a 120–240 V split phase service.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] If the neutral is broken along the return path to the circuit breaker panel, devices connected from a 120 V leg to the neutral may experience excess voltage, up to twice normal.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Low line voltage can cause electromechanical relays to repeatedly turn off and on, or "chatter".
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] If current is flowing through the load contacts, it causes arcing across the contacts as they open.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] The arcing can oxidize, pit, and melt the contacts.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] This process can increase the contact resistance, superheat the relay, and lead to fires.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Power fault circuit interrupters are designed to prevent fires from low voltage across loads.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] AFCIs may interfere with the operation of some power line communication technologies.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] An **arc lamp** or **arc light** is a lamp that produces light by an electric arc (also called a voltaic arc).
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] The carbon arc light, which consists of an arc between carbon electrodes in air, invented by Humphry Davy in the first decade of the 1800s, was the first practical electric light.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] It was widely used starting in the 1870s for street and large building lighting until it was superseded by the incandescent light in the early 20th century.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] It continued in use in more specialized applications where a high intensity point light source was needed, such as searchlights and movie projectors until after World War II.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] The carbon arc lamp is now obsolete for most of these purposes, but it is still used as a source of high intensity ultraviolet light.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] The term is now used for gas discharge lamps, which produce light by an arc between metal electrodes through a gas in a glass bulb.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] The common fluorescent lamp is a low-pressure mercury arc lamp.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] The xenon arc lamp, which produces a high intensity white light, is now used in many of the applications which formerly used the carbon arc, such as movie projectors and searchlights.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] An *arc* is the discharge that occurs when a gas is ionized.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] A high voltage is pulsed across the lamp to "ignite" or "strike" the arc, after which the discharge can be maintained at a lower voltage.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] The "strike" requires an electrical circuit with an *igniter* and a ballast.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] The ballast is wired in series with the lamp and performs two functions.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] When the power is first switched on, the igniter/starter (which is wired in parallel across the lamp) sets up a small current through the ballast and starter.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] This creates a small magnetic field within the ballast windings.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] A moment later the starter interrupts the current flow from the ballast, which has a high inductance and therefore tries to maintain the current flow (the ballast opposes any change in current through it); it cannot, as there is no longer a 'circuit'.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] As a result, a high voltage appears across the ballast momentarily, to which the lamp is connected; therefore the lamp receives this high voltage across it which 'strikes' the arc within the tube/lamp.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] The circuit will repeat this action until the lamp is ionized enough to sustain the arc.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] When the lamp sustains the arc, the ballast performs its second function, to limit the current to that needed to operate the lamp.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] The lamp, ballast, and igniter are rating-matched to each other; these parts must be replaced with the same rating as the failed component or the lamp will not work.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] The colour of the light emitted by the lamp changes as its electrical characteristics change with temperature and time.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] Lightning is a similar principle where the atmosphere is ionized by the high potential difference (voltage) between earth and storm clouds.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] The temperature of the arc in an arc lamp can reach several thousand degrees Celsius.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] The outer glass envelope can reach 500 degrees Celsius, therefore before servicing one must ensure the bulb has cooled sufficiently to handle.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] Often, if these types of lamps are turned off or lose their power supply, one cannot restrike the lamp again for several minutes (called cold restrike lamps).
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] However, some lamps (mainly fluorescent tubes/energy saving lamps) can be restruck as soon as they are turned off (called hot restrike lamps).
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] The Vortek water-wall plasma arc lamp, invented in 1975 by David Camm and Roy Nodwell at the University of British Columbia, Vancouver, Canada, made the Guinness Book of World Records in 1986 and 1993 as the most powerful continuously burning light source at over 300 kW or 1.2 million candle power.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] In a **carbon arc lamp**, the electrodes are carbon rods in free air.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] To ignite the lamp, the rods are touched together, thus allowing a relatively low voltage to strike the arc.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] The rods are then slowly drawn apart, and electric current heats and maintains an arc across the gap.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] The tips of the carbon rods are heated and the carbon vaporizes.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] The rods are slowly burnt away in use, and the distance between them needs to be regularly adjusted in order to maintain the arc.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] Many ingenious mechanisms were invented to control the distance automatically, mostly based on solenoids.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] In one of the simplest mechanically regulated forms (which was soon superseded by more smoothly acting devices) the electrodes are mounted vertically.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] The current supplying the arc is passed in series through a solenoid attached to the top electrode.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] If the points of the electrodes are touching (as in start up) the resistance falls, the current increases and the increased pull from the solenoid draws the points apart.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] If the arc starts to fail the current drops and the points close again.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] The Yablochkov candle is a simple arc lamp without a regulator, but it has the drawback that the arc cannot be restarted (single use) and a limited lifetime of only a few hours.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] The spectrum emitted by a carbon-arc lamp is the closest to that of sunlight of any lamp.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] One of the first electric lights, their harsh, intense output usually limited their use to lighting large areas.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] Although invisible wavelengths were unknown at the time of their invention, unenclosed lamps were soon discovered to produce large amounts of infrared and harmful ultraviolet radiation not found in sunlight.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] If the arc was encased in a glass globe, it was found that many of these invisible rays could be blocked.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] However, carbon-arcs were soon displaced by safer, more efficient, versatile, and easier to maintain incandescent and gas-discharge lamps.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] Carbon-arc lamps are still used where a close approximation of sunlight is needed, for testing materials, paints, and coatings for wear, fading, or deterioration, or, for example, spacecraft materials that are to be exposed to sunlight at orbits closer than Earth's.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] The arc consists of pure carbon-vapor heated to a plasma state.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] However, the arc contributes very little of the light output, and is considered non-luminous, as most of its emission occurs in spectral lines in the violet and UV portions of the spectrum.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] Most of the carbon spectra occurs in a very broad line centered at 389 nm (UV-A, just outside the visual spectrum), and a very narrow line at 250 nm (UV-B), plus some other less-powerful lines in the UV-C.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] Most of the visible and IR radiation is produced from incandescence created at the positive electrode, or anode.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] Unlike the tungsten anodes found in other arc lamps, which remain relatively cool, carbon produces much higher resistance and the electrons are forced to enter the anode at the hottest point, generating tremendous amounts of heat that vaporizes the carbon and creates a pit in the anode's surface.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] This pit is heated from 6000 to 6500 degrees Fahrenheit (3300 to 3600 degrees Celsius, just below its melting point), causing it to glow very brightly with incandescence.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] Due to this, the electrodes were often placed at right angles from each other with the anode facing outward to keep from blocking its light output.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] Since carbon has the highest melting point of any element, it is the only lamp whose blackbody radiation is capable of nearly matching the Sun's temperature of 10,000 degrees Fahrenheit (5500 degrees Celsius), especially when filters are used to remove most of the IR and UV light.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] The concept of carbon-arc lighting was first demonstrated by Humphry Davy in the early 19th century, but sources disagree about the year he first demonstrated it; 1802, 1805, 1807 and 1809 are all mentioned.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] Davy used charcoal sticks and a two-thousand-cell battery to create an arc across a 4-inch (100 mm) gap.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] He mounted his electrodes horizontally and noted that, because of the strong convection flow of air, the arc formed the shape of an arch.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] He coined the term "arch lamp", which was contracted to "arc lamp" when the devices came into common usage.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] In the late nineteenth century, electric arc lighting was in wide use for public lighting.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] The tendency of electric arcs to flicker and hiss was a major problem.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] In 1895, Hertha Ayrton wrote a series of articles for *The Electrician*, explaining that these phenomena were the result of oxygen coming into contact with the carbon rods used to create the arc.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] In 1899, she was the first woman ever to read her own paper before the Institution of Electrical Engineers (IEE).
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] Her paper was "The Hissing of the Electric Arc".
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] The arc lamp provided one of the first commercial uses for electricity, a phenomenon previously confined to experiment, the telegraph, and entertainment.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] In the United States, there were attempts to produce arc lamps commercially after 1850, but the lack of a constant electricity supply thwarted efforts.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] Thus electrical engineers began focusing on the problem of improving Faraday's dynamo.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] The concept was improved upon by a number of people including William Edwards Staite and Charles F.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] It was not until the 1870s that lamps such as the Yablochkov candle were more commonly seen.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] In 1877, the Franklin Institute conducted a comparative test of dynamo systems.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] The one developed by Brush performed best, and Brush immediately applied his improved dynamo to arc-lighting, an early application being Public Square in Cleveland, Ohio, on April 29, 1879.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] Despite this, Wabash, Indiana claims to be the first city ever to be lit with "Brush Lights".
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] Four of these lights became active there on March 31, 1880.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] Wabash was a small enough city to be lit entirely by 4 lights, whereas the installation at Cleveland's Public Square only lit a portion of that larger city.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] In 1880, Brush established the Brush Electric Company.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] The harsh and brilliant light was found most suitable for public areas, such as Cleveland's Public Square, being around 200 times more powerful than contemporary filament lamps.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] The usage of Brush electric arc lights spread quickly.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] A total of over 6,000 lights were actually sold.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] There were three major advances in the 1880s: František Křižík invented in 1880 a mechanism to allow the automatic adjustment of the electrodes.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] The arcs were enclosed in a small tube to slow the carbon consumption (increasing the life span to around 100 hours).
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] *Flame arc lamps* were introduced where the carbon rods had metal salts (usually magnesium, strontium, barium, or calcium fluorides) added to increase light output and produce different colours.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] In the U.S., patent protection of arc-lighting systems and improved dynamos proved difficult and as a result the arc-lighting industry became highly competitive.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] Brush's principal competition was from the team of Elihu Thomson and Edwin J.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] These two had formed the American Electric Corporation in 1880, but it was soon bought up by Charles A.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] Coffin, moved to Lynn, Massachusetts, and renamed the Thomson-Houston Electric Company.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] Thomson remained, though, the principal inventive genius behind the company patenting improvements to the lighting system.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] Under the leadership of Thomson-Houston's patent attorney, Frederick P.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] Fish, the company protected its new patent rights.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] Coffin's management also led the company towards an aggressive policy of buy-outs and mergers with competitors.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] Both strategies reduced competition in the electrical lighting manufacturing industry.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] By 1890, the Thomson-Houston company was the dominant electrical manufacturing company in the U.S.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] Around the turn of the century arc-lighting systems were in decline, but Thomson-Houston controlled key patents to urban lighting systems.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] This control slowed the expansion of incandescent lighting systems being developed by Thomas Edison's Edison General Electric Company.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] Conversely, Edison's control of direct current distribution and generating machinery patents blocked further expansion of Thomson-Houston.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] The roadblock to expansion was removed when the two companies merged in 1892 to form the General Electric Company.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] Arc lamps were used in some early motion-picture studios to illuminate interior shots.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] One problem was that they produce such a high level of ultra-violet light that many actors needed to wear sunglasses when off camera to relieve sore eyes resulting from the ultra-violet light.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] The problem was solved by adding a sheet of ordinary window glass in front of the lamp, blocking the ultra-violet.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] By the dawn of the "talkies", arc lamps had been replaced in film studios with other types of lights.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] In 1915, Elmer Ambrose Sperry began manufacturing his invention of a high-intensity carbon arc searchlight.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] These were used aboard warships of all navies during the 20th century for signaling and illuminating enemies.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] In the 1920s, carbon arc lamps were sold as family health products, a substitute for natural sunlight.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] Arc lamps were superseded by filament lamps in most roles, remaining in only certain niche applications such as cinema projection, spotlights, and searchlights.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] In the 1950s and 1960s the high-power D.C. for the carbon-arc lamp of an outdoor drive-in projector would typically be supplied by a motor–generator combo (AC motor powering a DC generator).
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] Carbon arc lighting left its imprint on other film projection practices.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] The projectionist would watch the rod burn down by eye (though a peephole like a welder's glass) and replace the carbon rod when changing film reels.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/arc-lamps] The two-projector changeover setup largely disappeared in the 1970s with the advent of xenon projector lamps, being replaced with single-projector platter systems, though films would continue to be shipped to cinemas on 2,000-foot reels.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/automatic-generation-control] In an electric power system, **automatic generation control** (**AGC**) is a system for adjusting the power output of multiple generators at different power plants, in response to changes in the load.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/automatic-generation-control] Since a power grid requires that generation and load closely balance moment by moment, frequent adjustments to the output of generators are necessary.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/automatic-generation-control] The balance can be judged by measuring the system frequency; if it is increasing, more power is being generated than used, which causes all the machines in the system to accelerate.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/automatic-generation-control] If the system frequency is decreasing, more load is on the system than the instantaneous generation can provide, which causes all generators to slow down.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/automatic-generation-control] Before the use of automatic generation control, one generating unit in a system would be designated as the regulating unit and would be manually adjusted to control the balance between generation and load to maintain system frequency at the desired value.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/automatic-generation-control] The remaining units would be controlled with speed droop to share the load in proportion to their ratings.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/automatic-generation-control] With automatic systems, many units in a system can participate in regulation, reducing wear on a single unit's controls and improving overall system efficiency, stability, and economy.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/automatic-generation-control] Where the grid has tie interconnections to adjacent control areas, automatic generation control helps maintain the power interchanges over the tie lines at the scheduled levels.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/automatic-generation-control] Turbine generators in a power system have stored kinetic energy due to their large rotating masses.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/automatic-generation-control] All the kinetic energy stored in a power system in such rotating masses is a part of the grid inertia.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/automatic-generation-control] When system load increases, grid inertia is initially used to supply the load.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/automatic-generation-control] This, however, leads to a decrease in the stored kinetic energy of the turbine generators.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/automatic-generation-control] Since the mechanical power of these turbines correlates with the delivered electrical power, the turbine generators have a decrease in angular velocity, which is directly proportional to a decrease in frequency in synchronous generators.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/automatic-generation-control] The purpose of the turbine-governor control (TGC) is to maintain the desired system frequency by adjusting the mechanical power output of the turbine.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/automatic-generation-control] For steam turbines, steam turbine governing adjusts the mechanical output of the turbine by increasing or decreasing the amount of steam entering the turbine via a throttle valve.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/automatic-generation-control] Load-frequency control (LFC) is employed to allow an area to first meet its own load demands, then to assist in returning the steady-state frequency of the system, Δf, to zero.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/automatic-generation-control] Load-frequency control operates with a response time of a few seconds to keep system frequency stable.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/automatic-generation-control] The goal of economic dispatch is to minimize total operating costs in an area by determining how the real power output of each generating unit will meet a given load.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/automatic-generation-control] Generating units have different costs to produce a unit of electrical energy, and incur different costs for the losses in transmitting energy to the load.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/automatic-generation-control] An economic dispatch algorithm will run every few minutes to select the combination of generating unit power setpoints that minimizes overall cost, subject to the constraints of transmission limitation or security of the system against failures.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/automatic-generation-control] Further constraints may be imposed by the water supply of hydroelectric generation, or by the availability of sun and wind power.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/availability-factor] The **availability factor** of a power plant is the duration it achieves production of electricity divided by the duration that it was planned to produce electricity.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/availability-factor] In the field of reliability engineering, *availability factor* is known as operational availability, $A_{o}$ .
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/availability-factor] The capacity factor of a plant includes numerous other factors which determine the durations the plant is planned to produce electricity.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/availability-factor] A solar photovoltaic plant is not planned to operate in the dark of a night, hence unplanned maintenance occurring whilst the sun is set does not impact the availability factor.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/availability-factor] Periods of generation where only partial generation of planned capacity occurs may or may not be deducted from the availability factor.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/availability-factor] An example of partial generation is a power plant with four installed turbines planned to be concurrently operational, but one of those turbines subsequently requires unplanned maintenance.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/availability-factor] Where deductions are made the metric is titled *equivalent availability factor* (EAF).
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/availability-factor] The availability of a power plant varies greatly depending on the type of fuel, the design of the plant and how the plant is operated.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/availability-factor] Everything else being equal, plants that are run less frequently have higher availability factors because they require less maintenance and because more inspections and maintenance can be scheduled during idle time.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/availability-factor] Most thermal power stations, such as coal, geothermal and nuclear power plants, have availability factors between 70% and 90%.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/availability-factor] Newer plants tend to have significantly higher availability factors, but preventive maintenance is as important as improvements in design and technology.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/availability-factor] Gas turbines have relatively high availability factors, ranging from 80% to 99%.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/availability-factor] Gas turbines are commonly used for peaking power plants, co-generation plants and the first stage of combined cycle plants.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/availability-factor] Originally the term availability factor was used only for power plants that depended on an active, controlled supply of fuel, typically fossil or later also nuclear.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/availability-factor] The emergence of renewable energy such as hydro, wind and solar power, which operate without an active, controlled supply of fuel and which come to a standstill when their natural supply of energy ceases, requires a more careful distinction between the availability factor and the capacity factor.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/availability-factor] By convention, such zero production periods are counted against the capacity factor but not against the availability factor, which thus remains defined as depending on an active, controlled supply of fuel, along with factors concerning reliability and maintenance.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/availability-factor] A wind turbine cannot operate in wind speeds above a certain limit, which counts against its availability factor.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/availability-factor] With this definition, modern wind turbines which require very little maintenance, have very high availability factors, up to about 98%.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/availability-factor] Photovoltaic power stations which have few or no moving parts and which can undergo planned inspections and maintenance during night have an availability factor approaching or equal to 100% when the sun is shining.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] The company was founded in 1867 in Providence, Rhode Island, by partners Stephen Wilcox and George Babcock to manufacture and market Wilcox's patented water-tube boiler.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] In 1867, Stephen Wilcox, Jr. and his partner George Herman Babcock, of Providence, Rhode Island, patented their so-called safety boiler ("Improvements in Steam Generators", U.S.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] Its water was dispersed in many small tubes that resisted exploding when heated, a significant advance over conventional shell boilers, whose water was concentrated in a single container.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] When overheated, seams of the shell could burst, causing an explosion, often with fatal consequences.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] The water tube boiler had the added advantages that it could generate steam under higher pressure and more efficiently than existing designs.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] In 1878, Thomas Edison purchased B&W boiler No.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] In 1891, Babcock & Wilcox Ltd was established as a separate United Kingdom company, to be responsible for all sales outside the US and Cuba.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] In 1895, B&W supplied of steam furnaces of Kahrizak sugar factory, Tehran, Iran.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] In 1898, Robert Jurenka and Alois Seidl signed an agreement with the British division, Babcock & Wilcox Ltd, to make the Berlin, Germany Babcock sales office into a subsidiary of the British company; a factory in Oberhausen in the Ruhr district made the boiler designed by the American engineers.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] In 1902, New York City's first subway line was powered by B&W boilers.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] During 1907 and 1909, Theodore Roosevelt's Great White Fleet were powered by B&W Boilers.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] In 1915, The Babcock & Wilcox Company acquired the Dumbarton Weldless Tube Company Ltd., originally Kosmoid Tubes Ltd., with works in Dumbarton, Scotland (operational until 1997).
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] In 1923, both Babcock & Wilcox Ltd and The Babcock & Wilcox Company bought into The Goldie & McCulloch Company Ltd of Cambridge, Ontario, to form Babcock-Wilcox & Goldie-McCulloch Ltd in Canada.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] In 1929, B&W installed the world's first commercial size recovery boiler using the magnesium bisulfite process in Quebec, Canada.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] Between 1941 and 1945, B&W designed and delivered 4,100 marine boilers for combat and merchant ships, including 95 percent of the US fleet in Tokyo Bay at Japanese surrender.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] In 1942, the company developed the cyclone furnace.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] Between 1943 and 1945, B&W provided components, materials and process development for Manhattan Project.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] In 1948, Babcock and Wilcox was at the center of a labor dispute with the United Stone and Allied Products Workers of America.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] The National Labor Relations Board held that during captive audience meetings, the union was entitled to equal time.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] Between 1949 and 1952, B&W provided the 8 boilers for the SS *United States*, the fastest ocean liner ever constructed.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] Between 1953 and 1955, B&W designed and fabricated components for USS *Nautilus* (SSN-571), world's first nuclear-powered submarine.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] In 1961, B&W designed and supplied reactors for world's first commercial nuclear ship NS *Savannah*.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] In 1962, B&W designed and furnished reactor systems for B&W's first commercial reactor, Indian Point, NY, using HEU 233.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] In 1967, the name of Babcock-Wilcox & Goldie-McCulloch Ltd is changed to Babcock & Wilcox Canada Ltd.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] In 1975, B&W designed and built components for liquid metal fast breeder reactors.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] In 1975, the long-term business agreements with the British Babcock & Wilcox Ltd were ended.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] Subsequently, the British company was renamed Babcock International Group plc.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] In 1978, B&W designed and built the nuclear reactor that was involved in the Three Mile Island accident.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] In 1983, A known, unreported design failure in a B&W valve was found to be an initial cause for the Three Mile Island accident.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] In 1999, B&W was awarded the contract to develop fuel cells and steam reforming for US Navy.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] On February 22, 2000, B&W filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy in part as a result of thousands of claims for personal injury due to prolonged exposure to asbestos and asbestos fibers.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] Claims included asbestosis, lung cancer, pleural and peritoneal mesothelioma.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] As a condition of emerging from bankruptcy, B&W created a trust fund to compensate victims for amounts far less than settlements paid in individual personal injury lawsuits.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] After B&W emerged from bankruptcy in 2006, B&W and BWX Technologies, both subsidiaries of the McDermott International, Inc., merged on 26 November 2007 to form The Babcock & Wilcox Companies, headed by President John Fees.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] On June 10, 2009, B&W unveiled B&W Modular Nuclear Energy, LLC (B&W MNE).
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] On the same day, B&W MNE announced its plans to design and develop the B&W mPower reactor, a modular, scalable nuclear reactor.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] The B&W mPower reactor design is a 125 megawatt, passively safe Advanced Light Water Reactor (ALWR) (a Generation III reactor) with a below-ground containment structure.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] The reactor is set to be manufactured in a factory, shipped by rail, then buried underground.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] On May 12, 2010, B&W announced that it and its subsidiaries would be spun off from its parent company, McDermott International, Inc.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] The headquarters moved from Lynchburg, Virginia to Charlotte. and the company became The Babcock & Wilcox Company.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] On August 2, 2010, B&W began trading on the New York Stock Exchange as BWC.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] On June 30, 2015, Babcock & Wilcox completed a spinoff from BWX Technologies, its former parent company.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] The two companies began trading separately on July 1 when Babcock & Wilcox Enterprises, Inc. was listed on the New York Stock Exchange under the ticker symbol: BW.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] In 2016, in the UK, the company was ordered to change its name following a petition filed by Babcock International.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] On September 24, 2018, Babcock & Wilcox announced that it would move its corporate headquarters from Charlotte to Akron, Ohio, into space formerly occupied by the Goodyear Tire and Rubber Company prior to its move to a new building nearby.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/babcock-wilcox] On December 30, 2019, Babcock & Wilcox relocated its corporate headquarters from Barberton, Ohio, to Akron, Ohio.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/holborn-viaduct-power-station] The plant began running on 12 January 1882 (1882-01-12), three years after the invention of the carbon-filament incandescent light bulb.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/holborn-viaduct-power-station] It burnt coal to drive a steam engine which drove a 27-tonne (27-long-ton; 30-short-ton), 125 horsepower (93 kW) generator which produced direct current (DC) at 110 volts.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/holborn-viaduct-power-station] It initially lit 968 16-candle incandescent lamps to provide street lighting from Holborn Circus to St.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/holborn-viaduct-power-station] Martin's Le Grand, which was later expanded to 3,000 lamps.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/holborn-viaduct-power-station] The power station also provided electricity for private residences, which may have included nearby Ely Place.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/holborn-viaduct-power-station] Having run at a significant loss the station closed in September 1886, and the lamps were converted back to gas.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/holborn-viaduct-power-station] Edison opened a second coal-fired power station in September 1882 in the United States, at Pearl Street Station in New York City.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/holborn-viaduct-power-station] In 1878, the City of London Corporation had installed 16 electric arc lamps over the viaduct, but the experiment was discontinued within six months, and the bridge returned to gas lighting.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/holborn-viaduct-power-station] The Victoria Embankment was lit with electric lamps at around the same time, using the Yablochkov candles demonstrated at the Exposition Universelle in Paris in 1878.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/holborn-viaduct-power-station] The Holborn Viaduct project was preceded by two months by an electricity supply from a water wheel in Godalming, Surrey – the world's first public electricity supply.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/holborn-viaduct-power-station] This hydroelectric project was on a much smaller scale, however, with a 10 horsepower (7.5 kW) generator running 4 arc lamps and 27 incandescent lamps.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/holborn-viaduct-power-station] Lacking the legal precedent to lay underground cables (digging the street was the sole prerogative of the gas companies), Edison's associate Edward Hibberd Johnson discovered culverts existed on the Holborn Viaduct which would allow for electrical cables to be laid.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/holborn-viaduct-power-station] The American-built 'Jumbo' generator (named after P.T.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/holborn-viaduct-power-station] Barnum's circus elephant) was driven by a Porter-Allen steam engine built by Babcock & Wilcox.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/holborn-viaduct-power-station] The station was on Crown property and so could not be extended, and was running at a significant annual loss.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/holborn-viaduct-power-station] It closed in September 1886 (1886-09) and the lamps were converted back to gas.
[src:holborn-viaduct-power-station/holborn-viaduct-power-station] The building in which it was housed was destroyed by bombing during the Blitz, and the large building called 60 Holborn Viaduct has since subsumed the site.
